segments.text: This is Eric Norgello talking with Evelyn Butler at Austin City Planning Department concerning planning history in Austin.
You've been with Austin City Planning Department for how long now, Ms. Butler?
About 25 and a half years.
25 and a half years, all right.
And prior to that, had you worked in any other planning departments?
Has all your experience been with Austin?
All of it has been with Austin.
I did work one summer while I was at the University of Texas with the
Planning Department here in Austin.
Beginning with these preliminary questions, which we are just now looking over, could you tell me when the first legislative authorization of a comprehensive plan was in Austin?
When you're talking about legislative authorization, I'm sure that you consider that to be the state.
And I do not have that date.
And the same would go for legislative authorization of planning, not just the document for Austin.
Well, we have the city charter, which established the planning commission and the authority of the planning commission to authorize and have a master plan prepared.
I don't have that exact date, but I might be able to pick that up for you.
I do have the charter here.
And they have the amendments here, but I don't think they have the date on when that first went into effect.
But it was authorized by the city charter.
Throughout the years, Austin City has adopted a number of comprehensive plans.
Could you tell me what the dates of these various plans were?
There have been a number of plans that have been prepared.
There was no comprehensive plan adopted until June 8, 1961.
We had pieces that were adopted.
We had pieces that were used some, but were never adopted.
We had a plan that was prepared by Cook and Fowler in 19...
27, 28, and I think that that was used as a guide even though there was no official action taken that I can find.
Then in 1950 there was a plan that was generally prepared by Farron Granger and I think as a result of the work that they did the City Council adopted a thoroughfare plan and that just
set out the widths, the right-of-way widths and locations of a limited number of thoroughfares.
After that date, nothing was done until the city authorized consultants to be hired to prepare a new comprehensive plan or master plan for Austin.
Work was started on it in the mid-50s, and the work was completed, I believe, in 1958.
The plan went through a series of public hearings.
It was modified substantially before it was adopted in 1961.
After that date, we have ended up with a new comprehensive plan
But prior to that plan coming about, there were two amendments to the transportation section of the 61 plan.
The highway department jointly with the city and the county

conducted a transportation study and this transportation study resulted in the expressway and major arterial plan for Austin which replaced the 61 thoroughfare plan and it was first adopted in 67 and it was updated and adopted again with revisions in 1969.
That plan has been used up until
The new comprehensive plan came out, and we have now a roadway, Austin Metropolitan roadway plan that was adopted just a few months ago.
Let's see.
You mentioned that the adopted comprehensive plans in Austin have been revised from time to time.
Could you tell me how this revision takes place?
Any applicant or city agency who might feel that change is in order for the plan, whether the 61 plan covered land use as well as the transportation system.
Whenever we had a proposal for deviation from that plan covering a fairly major area, we came through with what we called a master plan change.
accepted an application from whoever wanted to change the plan.
We prepared maps.
We sent out memos to all the departments to find out how that would affect their area of responsibility.
Then we held the public hearing.
We would have the individual notices to people immediately around the area.
and newspaper notice for the hearing.
The hearing would be held before the Planning Commission and then their recommendation would be passed on to the City Council and the City Council would take action.
We have had a series of changes both in land use and in thoroughfare locations.
Is there any systematic, periodic review of the city's comprehensive plan?

It was scheduled to be reviewed annually, but it was not followed through in that sense for the simple reason that as people saw problems with the plan, the amendments were brought up whenever the need arose rather than waiting for an annual review.
The new plan, there will be
I think review of that, I think we'll be following a schedule in regard to reevaluating the new comprehensive plan.
So Austin's found that it's more feasible to revise a plan as needed rather than on a regularly scheduled basis?
Not necessarily.
We have always felt that review would be the best because that way then you can look at the overall picture rather than at just one area.
Now, there are some modifications that would not call for a complete review, but there are others that can be very, very influential on other areas, and it should not be done on a piecemeal basis.
How is this review undertaken, then?
The review...
The process itself.
The process itself would be that if we had
an area that was developing with development pressures that would not, say, meet the comprehensive plan.

And we would feel as though that maybe the comprehensive plan did not take some of these things into consideration, possibly because we did not have the knowledge at the time it was prepared, or possibly because we've had other pressures from outside investments.
that were not known at the time the plan was prepared.
I think that this can be evidenced by the number of environmental concerns that have been raised in recent years.
We have come up with a series of new ordinances that have covered, say, our Lake Austin watershed in order to maintain
our safe water supply because Lake Austin provides Austin with the drinking water.
We have some very sensitive aquifers in the Austin area and we have had a series of ordinances that are
key to the environmental issue and the maintaining of the aquifers so that we do not end up with pollutants entering the aquifer.
So in those areas, even though the plans as we've gone through them through the years, some of this information was not readily available.
We've had new technology.
We've had new interests as far as environmental concerns.
have been raised.
And so I think we ended up, even though our plan, the 61 plan, I think, was intended to go into the 80s.
And of course, we didn't adopt the new plan, I don't believe, until 79.
No, let's see, it might have been early 1980.
But we'd had so many changes in the interim that a number of the land uses, for instance, were really no longer valid.

Would you say that looking at past history of planning here, that Austin conducts its planning in a comprehensive manner, or would you characterize it in a different type of way, such as incremental planning, radical planning, response to crises, or something like that?
Well, I don't think that we can put it into one specific category.
Austin, I think, has made every effort to go in for the comprehensive planning for the city.
We have...
had the review of, for instance, the plans, as I've mentioned, the thoroughfare plan, and we have tried to do that on an entire city and area-wide basis.
We have worked with other communities that abut our ETJ or where we might have overlaps of ETJ.
We have worked with them on a long-range
concept to where we can work together.
I think that we generally would fall into the category of the comprehensive rather than the either radical or incremental.
Now there are times when we have, say, some development pressures when an industry wants to come in.
And I feel as though that that is where we...
might consider the incremental for the simple reason that if the industry had not been anticipated in the early stages, then we find that that industry can have quite an impact on the community.
And we many times have a very short review time of how that industry would impact the community.
We make every effort to go into
review of the utility situation, the traffic situation that would be generated by it, and the effect on existing development.
And I think that the work that has been done in regard to a number of these industries has been fairly comprehensive.
Do you happen to recall when the first zoning ordinance was in Austin?
I think that it was in the mid-20s.
I don't have the exact date for you, and I would like to get that for you.
Would you happen to know if zoning ordinances happened to be enacted before the city had a comprehensive plan?
I think they were.
What would be the basis of that kind of authority for zoning then?
That, I can't give you the history.
I wish I could.
But I think the idea was that there would be certain places that businesses were located on major streets and
I think that some of the early zoning took place by strip zoning because they felt as though this is where the activity would take place.
What administrative procedures and planning program elements does your community presently have for implementing community plans?
What do you mean by community plans?
Comprehensive plans.
All right.
The implementation of the comprehensive plan goes back to

zoning ordinance, subdivision ordinance, the capital improvements program, and then there are a number of individual plans like public facilities plan, fire service, or I'm not sure what the title is, but fire station location plan, and we have a parks and recreation plan.
And all of these tie back into the CIP program,
and the funding that would be required to implement these plans.
When did Austin City first establish a planning department?
I believe the planning department was established in 1949 or 50.
And at present, could you tell me approximately how many professional planners the city employs?
At this time?
I'd have to check the number.
I think that I could... Could I give this to you a little later in the interview?
Sure.
Or could you cut this off, and I think I can get...

The number of planners, professional planners, that we have on staff now, including our administration, would be 24, and this can fluctuate 24, 26, right in that area because we are short two at the present time.
And this covers advanced planning and current planning.
Has the size of the department over the years expanded to meet the needs of the city?
We had a little expansion, not very much.
Our workload has continued to grow, and actually our staff has not grown as much as our workload has grown.
So you would say you had approximately the same size staff five years ago?
Oh, it might vary two or three, not very many.
We were authorized

a new person just within the last couple of months because we have added a new section to the zoning ordinance which calls for review of all site plans for development along some of our major roadways.
We also had the Barton Creek ordinance which was implemented and we were authorized a new position to help
implement that ordinance.
So we have expanded a little, but not as rapidly as our workload has expanded.
Could you give me some information on the organizational structure of the planning department here?
We actually have two sections within the department at this time.
We have the current planning section and the advanced planning section.
And we consider the administration, our director, assistant director, and the supporting staff for that administrative function.

The advanced planning section normally carries through, say, the writing and preparation of the comprehensive plan, and they are responsible for a number of studies in relation to implementing that plan.
The current planning section takes care of the day-to-day operation.
The current planning section actually is divided up into three subsections.
subdivision processing, subdivision design, and zoning.
Now, I do have another more or less support section for both of those, which is the drafting section.
And that gives me an idea on chain of command within each of the sections.
Right.
But within the current planning, there are, in other words, all the day-to-day operations.
Now, we do have some crossover, even though the drafting section is under the supervision of current planning.
It still does some work for advanced planning.
Advanced planning carries out some studies that benefit us.
They have an artist on their staff, and so some preparation in regard to some of our publications might be done by advanced planning, so we do have quite a bit of crossover.
Could you give me an idea as to relationship of the planning department and
its legislative body, that is the Planning Commission, and what type of member within the department acts as liaison and some ideas to communication within the two bodies?
All right.
Actually, the Planning Department is the staff for the Planning Commission.
Mr. Lilly, our director, is the executive secretary of the
Planning Commission, and we're responsible for maintaining all the records, minutes, and the support for the public hearings conducted by the Planning Commission.
So, actually, Mr. Lilly appears at, I'd say, the majority of the Planning Commission meetings.
We do have other staff.
We have subdivision processing planner appearing
in regard to subdivisions.

We have several zoning staff members appearing for the Planning Commission meetings that hold the public hearings on zoning, special permits, the principal roadway area, historic zoning, which also goes through the Landmark Commission.
How would you describe the relationship
of the Planning Department and various citizen groups that try to impact the advice that's given to the Planning Commission?
I think it's excellent.
We, of course, have had some concerns raised by citizen groups at times that they feel as though they don't get as much information as they would like to have.
send out information to them.
We have a list of neighborhood associations that I think total close to 100.
And we notify the neighborhood association affected on each zoning case if there is one.
I mean, if there is an association, they're given a notice just like a property owner would be given notice.
How well organized are these neighborhood action groups?
Some of them are very well organized.
Others have organized as a result of, say, a zoning issue that they are unhappy with.
And so that...
many times initiates the development of the neighborhood association.

Do you find that in your contact with these neighborhood groups, they seem to be interested in specific neighborhood aerial interests, or they have a broader perspective, let's say a comprehensive view of the city and its city's needs in that?
I would say that a few of them have indicated that they have an interest in
the entire city.

There are some that have appeared on issues that are outside of their immediate neighborhood, but there are others who are just very neighborhood-oriented and they're concerned only when their own area is threatened.
Within any city, significant events historically will impact the city in many ways, planning being one of them.

Looking at some of the different types of events that can impact a city's planning, could you tell me something about the founding of the city of Boston and whether it was planned and how planning was later affected by its founding?
Well, I think that when Austin was first laid out, we had some very...
This was when?
I wish you had not asked me that question.
In checking records, I find that it was actually, the city was incorporated in December of 1839.
Do you happen to know if the city was planned at that time, whether there was any kind of a layout for streets or design?
There was a layout.
I think that that might have come a little bit later, because I vaguely remember a map that's labeled 1840.
that shows the downtown area.
It shows out the laying out of Congress, East Avenue, West Avenue, and the original outlocks for the city of Austin.
And I believe that's, it might be dated 1839, but somewhere or other I feel as though, and it could be tied to the date that it was officially built.
settled, and I could get that information for you and maybe provide you with a copy of that map.
Has the city of Austin been influenced in a planning sense by city fairs or county fairs or larger expositions or major conventions over the years?
Not in, I don't think, a major sense.
I think that there were some celebrations in the early days, but I don't think that they were that extensive, and
I just don't recall enough history on that to be able to respond adequately.
During the frontier period, could you tell me what functions the city of Austin performed in relationship to the state or to the West?
Of course, the capital of the state.
That's the primary function.
I think that because it had a very central location being located on the Colorado River,
It was one of the trading posts for a lot of areas around Austin.
I feel as though that with the railroad coming to Austin, it really functioned as a hub for Central Texas.
That's my next question on the coming of the railroad.
How did this impact planning in Austin?
Well, one thing, because our transportation system was keyed more to railroad than anything else, the very best homes in Austin were built close to the railroad.
That's not the way it is today, but it was then, and we have some very old historic homes that were constructed close to the railroad facility.
During world wars, typically, United States governments have established military bases that didn't exist previously.
An influx of population will impact the area.
Did Austin have any problems with this and have to plan for that?
Austin actually, I think, participated in as much as I understand that the Bergstrom Air Force Base, that the land was given by the city of Austin to the government for the base.
And I think that there's always been a very good relationship between the city of Austin and the Air Force Base.

We have, of course, a number of people who have been brought here as a result of it, and it has had, I think, a very long-range effect on Austin, inasmuch as so many people who come to Austin by way of Bergstrom find that Austin is one of the most delightful places to live.
And when they retire, even though they might have been transferred to another section of the country,
We have a number of people, military people, who have come back to Austin to retire.
It also affects our employment.
This department has a number of retired Air Force people working in it at the present time.
They have gone on to start a second profession after they have completed their training
well, tour of duty or whatever you might want to call it.
And they have started a second career, and they are, I think, functioning very well in the employment market as well as in the retirement.
Did the number of people coming with Bergstrom Air Force Base entail any special planning needs as regards that area of the city and service provision?
I'm sure it did affect a good bit of planning in the early days.
It was before I came here, and I'm not sure how much of an impact it had at that time when it first came.
In later years, it has affected housing development because the personnel had to be on call so that they could reach the base within a certain number of minutes, I believe.
And so I think that it helped increase the population in the South Austin area.

I think that is another reason that since we had so many military people living in that area, there was a delay in getting as many, say, shopping centers in South Austin as we had in North Austin and other areas because a lot of their shopping was done on the base, and even though we had the residential development,
The commercial development really did not quite meet the same standards as it did in other areas.

Now, I don't think that that is quite the case anymore because as our population has grown, I don't think the Bergstrom population has grown as fast as the other population, so that's beginning to balance out.
Can you see even at this point or the point where you...
in the 1950s when you joined the department, any transportation needs that were impacted by coming to the Air Force Base, thoroughfares widening?
Well, we did have, for instance, Riverside Drive was a county lane, and that was one of the main streets that was used by Bergstrom personnel to come into Austin.
And, of course, I think that
More than likely, the Montopolis interchange had the need for it, was generated partially by Bergstrom.
And I think that the need for building up Riverside Drive was partially by Bergstrom.
But again, it's just a small percentage in the overall.
The Great Depression in the 1930s and the New Deal programs that were enacted to deal with the problem had a great impact on many cities.
For example, WPA projects, funding for planning and development.
What role did this play in planning in Austin?
The only thing that I can give you without doing some research is that we did have a number of WPA projects.
I think that some of the facilities out in Zilker Park were built at that time.
I know that there were a number of things that happened throughout Austin during that period, and I do not have the exact locations, but we did benefit, I think,
indirectly from the WPA activity.
Can you think of any public buildings or city buildings that were constructed as a result of WPA funding?
Well, I think the ones in Zilker Park are the main ones that I can think of.
City administration buildings or city hall or anything like that?
I don't think so.
I don't believe so.
The urban renewal era in late 60s and early to mid 1970s, what impact did that have on planning in Austin and development here?
Well, I would say that it had quite a bit of impact
inasmuch as urban renewal was used in a number of areas.
We had a series of projects.
One was called the Bracken Ridge Urban Renewal Area.
That was for the expansion of Bracken Ridge Hospital and the related area.
We used urban renewal for the expansion of the university.
Then there were several projects in East Austin that did not tie into the public agency need.
that were for the neighborhoods.
I think urban renewal has mixed reception here in Austin.
We had a number of people who were displaced in the university area.
They would have been displaced whether it had come under urban renewal or otherwise because the university
did have the right of eminent domain and they could have expanded and the legislature had already decided that the property would be acquired.
And one reason that urban renewal was used...
